The headline is 80 cents of the dollar (Ogilvy). Five times more people read the headline than the body copy. So if your headline is weak, nothing else matters.

On length:
The data is pretty clear — shorter wins for headlines, longer can work for subheadlines.
For headlines specifically, the sweet spot is 6-12 words. Sumo's study of 150K+ headlines found that straightforward headlines outperformed clever ones 88% of the time (15.4% CTR vs 7.1%). People don't want to decode your headline. They want to immediately understand the value.
For subheadlines, you have more room — typically 15-25 words. The sub's job is to expand on the headline promise and bridge into the first paragraph. Think of it as the headline's wingman.

The headline formulas that actually convert:
The research showed these consistently outperform:
Specific result formula: "We Help Supplement Brands Generate $100K+ in Monthly Email Revenue in 90 Days" — hits dream outcome, specificity, timeframe, niche callout all at once.
How-to without the objection: "How to 3X Your Email Revenue Without Hiring a Single In-House Marketer" — the "without" is doing a lot of heavy lifting. It pre-handles the #1 objection in the headline itself.
Case study formula: "How One Supplement Brand Added $214K in Email Revenue in 60 Days" — social proof baked directly into the headline. People see themselves in the story.
Testimonial headline: Just lead with a client quote as the headline. Research showed a 24% conversion lift.
The number formula: Headlines with specific numbers get meaningfully higher CTRs. Odd, unrounded numbers ("$47,382" not "$50,000") feel more credible because they imply measurement.

The 3-second test:
Show your headline to someone who doesn't know your business. After 3 seconds, cover it and ask them to explain what you do. If they can't — rewrite it. The headline needs to immediately answer: what do you do, who is it for, and why should I care.

One rule that overrides everything:
Match your headline to your traffic temperature. Cold traffic (Meta ads) needs a benefit or curiosity headline — not a brand name. Warm traffic (retargeting, email list) can handle a more direct offer headline. Getting this wrong is the single biggest conversion killer most agencies miss.

Headline formulas that convert for this exact niche

Sumo's analysis of 150,000+ opt-in headlines revealed that **straightforward headlines outperformed creative alternatives 88% of the time**. A direct headline converted at 15.42% versus 7.1% for a clever question-format variant — more than double. Lovable.dev's data from thousands of A/B tests showed headline optimization delivers **27–104% conversion lifts**. For an email marketing agency targeting supplement and eCom brands, these are the highest-performing formulas:

**The Specific Result Formula** is the strongest performer for cold traffic: "We Help Supplement Brands Generate $100K+ in Monthly Email Revenue in 90 Days." Number-based headlines are preferred by 36% of readers, and dollar amounts resonate powerfully with business owners.

**The "How To… Without…" Formula** removes objections inline: "How to 3X Your Email Revenue Without Hiring a Single In-House Marketer." This combines benefit with fear removal.

**The Case Study Formula** leads with social proof: "How One Supplement Brand Added $214K in Email Revenue in 60 Days." Ideal for cold traffic where prospects need immediate proof.

**The Testimonial Headline** delivered a **24.31% conversion lift** in LKR Social Media's test: "'They Added $83K in Email Revenue in Our First Month Together' — Brand Founder."

**The Authority Formula** works best for warm traffic: "The Email Marketing Team Behind 7 and 8-Figure Supplement Brands."

**Headlines to A/B test first:**
- "We Help Supplement Brands Add $50K–$200K/Month in Email Revenue"
- "How [Brand Name] Added $127K in Email Revenue in 60 Days"
- "Stop Leaving 30–40% of Your Revenue on the Table"

A critical rule from CXL's Peep Laja: test whether someone unfamiliar can explain your offer after reading just your headline. If they can't, no amount of traffic will fix the clarity problem. And per Ogilvy's still-valid principle, five times as many people read the headline as read the body copy.
